          "body": "Verse 30 is Proverbs 21's theological apex: 'There is no wisdom, no understanding, no counsel against the LORD.' The three terms nullified — chokhmah (wisdom), tavunah (understanding), etsah (counsel) — are the very vocabulary Proverbs uses to commend the highest human virtues. To say there is 'none against the LORD' is not to dismiss wisdom but to locate it properly: genuine wisdom never stands against God, and whatever wisdom imagines itself capable of overturning His purposes is, by definition, not wisdom at all. The verse answers every implicit question raised by the chapter's suffering of the righteous, the temporary prosperity of the wicked, and the anxiety of preparation before battle. Human plans matter; human wisdom matters; but there is a ceiling above which no human strategy reaches. Verse 31 gives the practical application: prepare the horse — do not neglect means — but rest the outcome on the God who holds victory alone."
