        "body": "Proverbs 21's extended portrait of the wicked is notable for one consistent feature: their strategies are self-defeating. They do not merely fail to prosper — they actively produce their own ruin. Verse 6 captures this with the word hevel (vapor, vanity — Ecclesiastes' signature word): the treasure accumulated by lying is already disappearing at the moment of acquisition. The phrase 'pursuit of death' (mevaqqeshei mavet — literally 'those seeking death') frames the liar not as someone who stumbled into danger but as someone energetically hunting their own destruction without knowing it.\n\nVerse 7 sharpens this: the wicked person's violence — shod, the violent destruction they inflict on others — becomes the instrument of their own sweeping away. They refuse mishpat (justice); justice refuses to protect them. The same social order they exploit turns and consumes them. Verse 12 is the chapter's most theologically complex verse. The 'Righteous One' who considers the house of the wicked is either (a) a righteous human observer — a judge or a wise person — or (b) God Himself acting as the Righteous One. The Hebrew tsaddiq without a definite article could be either. Given the chapter's consistent emphasis on divine sovereignty, and the parallel in Proverbs 29:2, many interpreters (following Calvin's reading) see the divine Tsaddiq here — God surveilling and overturning the wicked's household. Both readings are within orthodox bounds; the divine reading gives the verse greater canonical force.\n\nThe sacrifice bracket (21:27, echoing 21:3) closes the wicked's portrait with its most damning detail: religious practice with 'evil intent' (zimmah — deliberately purposed wickedness). The wicked person in verse 27 is not ignorant of religion; he performs it. But he performs it while intending to maintain his wickedness — using the sacrificial system as a cover or a transaction rather than a genuine expression of submission to God. The aph ki ('how much more') is the chapter's only explicit escalation marker, signaling that this is the worst case among bad cases.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Hevel* (vapor, 21:6) — Qoheleth's signature word for vanity, ephemerality; its use here places lying-tongue wealth in the same category as all futile human striving under the sun. *Shod* (violence, 21:7) — destructive violence, often plunder; the word recurs in the prophets' indictments of oppression. *Zimmah* (evil intent, 21:27) — deliberately purposed wickedness; used in Leviticus 18-19 for the gravest moral violations."
