        "excerpt": "He who pursues righteousness and loyalty finds life, righteousness and honor.",
        "body": "The chapter's positive anthropology is concentrated in verse 21, but the preceding verses build toward it. Verse 15 establishes that justice is not merely tolerable to the righteous — it is simchah (joy, gladness). The righteous person experiences justice as delight, not duty. This is the character difference Proverbs consistently draws: not that the righteous and the wicked perform different actions, but that they have different desires. The righteous desires justice; the wicked person's soul craves evil (21:10, nephesh of the wicked craves ra).\n\nVerse 18 introduces one of Proverbs' most striking providential claims: the wicked become kopher (ransom, cover-price) for the righteous. The word kopher is used in the Mosaic law for the price paid to redeem life (Exodus 21:30; Numbers 35:31). In Proverbs' wisdom worldview, the social and historical order ultimately works out so that the wicked absorb the consequences that would otherwise fall on the upright — not as a mechanical legal exchange, but as a general providential pattern. Isaiah 43:3-4 gives the same language eschatologically (Egypt as ransom for Israel). The reader is meant to take comfort that divine justice eventually inverts the apparent advantage of the wicked.\n\nVerse 21's pursuit-language (radaph, to chase relentlessly) is the chapter's call to active moral agency. The verse's grammar is elegant: the one who pursues tsedaqah and chesed finds tsedaqah — the righteousness pursued is given back as a found possession, along with chay (life) and kavod (honor, weight, glory). The reward exceeds the investment; you hunt righteousness and come home with life and glory as well. Tim Keller's observation about the gospel's reversal-logic applies here: the one who loses life (by the standards of self-protective acquisition) finds it; the one who pursues righteousness rather than security ends up with both.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Chesed* (loving devotion, 21:21) — the richest OT theological term for covenant faithfulness; its pairing with tsedaqah appears throughout the Psalms (Psalm 85:10; 89:14) as the two pillars of God's own character, now here applied as the believer's pursuit. *Radaph* (pursues, 21:21) — to chase, hunt down; the same verb used of enemies in pursuit; the righteous person hunts virtue with that intensity. *Kavod* (honor, 21:21) — literally weight, glory; the same word used of the divine glory-presence (kavod Yahweh)."
